From Allen Tobias Subject Re Advantages of Slip Ons In article Dave Schlotthauer writes Quick question What are the advantages of slip on's versus your stock exhaust versus aftermarket exhaust systems I don't see many people using slip on's but they are heavily advertised and half as Thanks Dave Cost is lower than OEM replacements and they weigh Also in most instances you do not have to rejet the carburetors to get a little more I replaced my OEM canister with an Ontario systems slip The mid range performance is better but I also notice a slight stumble at After talking to Kaz Yoshima the developer and manufacturer of the slip on he thinks I might need larger pilot idle Was not suppose to but maybe where I live makes a Altitude barometric Anyway besides that minor glitch I like the slip on performance and the sound which is louder than stock but not loud enough to annoy The Ontario slip on use some sort of sound baffling technique to reduce the sound at full Just remember every bike is a tuned When you change the intake or exhaust characteristics beyond the allowable delta of the manufacturer you may have to change other areas to Like a complete change of the exhaust system header and muffler changes the exhaust characteristic to the point which re jetting is required to compensate for the new engine breathing pumping Talk with the folks who make the slip on you intend to use and ask them if they have used it on your particular Check with people who have the system also to see what they think about there slip Also as a last data point in Sport Rider's first issue did a review on a group of header and exhaust systems for the They also included as a side bar the Ontario slip on the Dyno showed an increase from stock of at the rear wheel verses Buyer beware of outrageous claimed increases in horse power It may have been true in the past but not today AT Allen Tobias Technical email Convex Computer Marketing Waterview Parkway Richardson TX This bike is awesome and I'm L